    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-01-27T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-01-27T16:00:00-05:00" n="535"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d535">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 Defense (M)/4078 Suppl.: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-01-27T16:00:00-05:00"
                            >January 27, 1942—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>49. Department’s 14, January 10, 3 p.m. The Department understands through K. C.
                    Li that word has been received from Dr. H. H. Kung to the effect that, because
                    of prior commitments of 1 or 2,000 tons to Great Britain and 4,000 tons to the
                    Soviet Union, the maximum shipments of wolframite to this country, including the
                        <hi rend="italic">Tulsa</hi> shipment, will be 15,000 tons. Dr. Kung added,
                    however, that the National Resources Commission had been directed to exert every
                    effort in production toward attaining a 1942 goal of 20,000 tons for the United
                    States.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
